GWAS-by-subtraction - AN conditioned on BMI

Karanvir Singh

2023-03-19

Results

Genomic SEM (GWAS-by-subtraction)

Using summary statistics from the 2019 AN GWAS (Watson et. al) and 2018 BMI GWAS (Yengo et. al). BMI GWAS sumstats are imputed against 1KG EUR reference panel by me using RAISS. There are 3,255,926 SNPs for which I have both marginal and conditional effect sizes (a subset of the 7,328,751 AN SNPs and 3,909,793 BMI-imputed SNPs).

After merging the sumstats, I have:

  1. 117 genome-wide significant SNPs in AN sumstats
  2. 75,913 genome-wide significant SNPs in BMI sumstats
  3. 104 genome-wide significant SNPs after conditioning on BMI

Change in effect sizes

All 104 SNPs that reach genome-wide significance in the conditioned results are also genome-wide significant in the anorexia sumstats.

The forestplot here shows the marginal and conditional effect sizes for the 117 AN GWS SNPs.

# Am I comparing the effect sizes to the wrong reference? The sumstats function in genomicSEM scales the betas relative to unit-variance scaled phenotypes

p_sumstats_imp %>% mutate(AN_LOWER = beta.AN - 1.96*se.AN,
         AN_HIGHER = beta.AN + 1.96*se.AN,
         CON_LOWER = BETA.con - 1.96*SE.con,
         CON_HIGHER = BETA.con + 1.96*SE.con,
         BMI_HIGHER = beta.BMI + 1.96*se.BMI,
         BMI_LOWER = beta.BMI - 1.96*se.BMI) %>%
  filter(P.AN < 5e-8) %>% 
  ggplot(data=., ) +
        geom_pointrange(aes(x=SNP, y=beta.AN, ymin=AN_LOWER, ymax=AN_HIGHER), alpha=0.5) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(x=SNP, y=BETA.con, ymin=CON_LOWER, ymax=CON_HIGHER), lty=2, alpha=0.5, col="red")+
  geom_pointrange(aes(x=SNP, y=beta.BMI, ymin=BMI_LOWER, ymax=BMI_HIGHER), lty=3, alpha=0.5, col="blue")+
        geom_hline(yintercept=0, lty=2) +  # add a dotted line at x=0 after flip
        coord_flip() +  # flip coordinates (puts labels on y axis)
        xlab("Sig. SNP") + ylab("BETA (95% CI)") +
  ggtitle("Marginal and conditional effect sizes of GWS AN SNPs")+
        theme_bw()  # use a white background

I use plink to calculate pairwise r^2 between the watson lead SNPs and all SNPs in a 3MB window around them, to identify which of the lead SNPs in the subset of data tag the lead SNPs in the original data.

plink --bfile EUR_phase3_autosomes --r2 --ld-snp-list watsonleads.txt  --ld-window-kb 3000 --ld-window 99999 --ld-window-r2 0

Each of the 8 lead SNPs from the Watson paper has a corresponding SNP in my subset that is in high LD (>0.6, so not independent).

leadLD <- read.table("plink.ld", header=TRUE)
subset_LD <- leadLD %>% filter(SNP_B %in% p_sumstats_imp$SNP) %>%
  left_join(., p_sumstats_imp %>% select(SNP, P.AN), by=c("SNP_B"="SNP"))

tagSNPs <- subset_LD %>% group_by(SNP_A) %>% slice_min(order_by = P.AN, with_ties = FALSE)

Non-imputed BMI SNPs

Just to make sure the additional imputation step using RAISS (to increase the number of SNPs in the intersection of the two GWASs), I also fit the model using the not-imputed BMI sumstats. There are now 1,877,083 SNPs for which I have marginal and conditional effect sizes.

68 GWS AN SNPs 59 GWS AN-conditioned-on-BMI SNPs.

# load p_sumstats
load("/home/karan099/scratch/scripts/gwas-by-subtraction/AN-minus-BMI-not-imputed/Sumstats.RData")

# load conditioned results
conditionedAN_notIMP <- vroom::vroom("/home/karan099/scratch/scripts/gwas-by-subtraction/AN-minus-BMI-not-imputed/an-conditioned-bmi-not-imputed-google-model.tsv")

# change column names
conditionedAN_notIMP <- conditionedAN_notIMP %>% rename(BETA.con = "BETA",
                          P.con = "P",
                          SE.con = "SE")

#load not imputed bmi sumstats
bmi_not_imp <- vroom::vroom("/home/karan099/project/ksingh/data/summary_stats/Munged/BMI_2018.tsv.gz")

# Merge p_sumstats with conditioned betas, se and p
p_sumstats_not_imp <- left_join(p_sumstats, conditionedAN_notIMP %>% select(SNP, BETA.con, P.con, SE.con))

# Add anorexia and BMI p values to p sumstats
p_sumstats_not_imp <- left_join(p_sumstats_not_imp, an_sumstats %>% select(SNP, P), by="SNP") %>%
  left_join(., bmi_not_imp %>% select(SNP, P), by="SNP", suffix=c(".AN", ".BMI"))

The following table shows the effect sizes for each tag SNP as calculated through the model fitted on either the imputed BMI sumstats, or the non-imputed (original) sumstats. The tag SNP in each case is identical, and the results show that the additional imputing step does not change the conditioned betas or P-values of the tag SNPs. In both cases, the SNPs tagging lead SNPs rs10747478, rs13100344 and rs2008387 are not significant at the genome-wide significance level after conditioning on BMI.

To note, I do not have a GWS tag SNP for lead SNP rs13100344. Additionally, SNP rs2008387 although not significant is still borderline genome-wide significant (p=1.725e-08, p_con = 5.2961e-08)

mtCOJO

I ran mtCOJO using the same subet of SNPs in both cases (imputed or not imputed).

When using the non-imputed SNPs (n = 1,877,083), I have 62 GWS SNPs after conditioning, and all 62 are also GWS before conditioning (out of 68).
